CaseSummary.Summary: Vehicle one (V1 - case vehicle), a 1996 Chevrolet Lumina, 4-door sedan was traveling east in the eastbound lane of a two-lane, two-way roadway. It was daylight, cloudy, and the bituminous road was dry. The driver of V1 reportedly experienced brake failure and in an effort to slow the vehicle, he drove off the right side of the road and entered a shallow ditch. V1 traveled a short distance and the front of V1 struck a large tree (28-cm diameter). V1 was towed due to disabling vehicle damage. The 34-year-old male driver of V1 was using the available three-point seat belt and the steering-wheel airbag deployed. The 14-year-old male right-front passenger (case occupant) was using the available three-point seat belt and the dash-mounted airbag deployed. Both occupants of V1 were transported via ground ambulance to different local hospitals and the case occupant was later transferred to a regional level-one trauma center.

CirenCaseForm.InjuryAnalysis:
The case occupant is the 175 cm (5' 9"), 159 kg (394 lb), 14-year-old male right-front passenger of a 1996 Chevrolet Impala, 4-door sedan. The case vehicle ran off the right side of the road and struck a tree with the center-front bumper. The impact was classified as severe. The WinSmash reconstruction program calculated a delta-v of 77 kmph (48 mph), which appeared to be consistent with the observed vehicle damage. The case occupant was using the available three-point seat belt. The dash-mounted airbag deployed.
In response to the 12 o'clock direction of force (360 degrees), he moved forward, relative to the vehicle interior. He sustained a loss of consciousness probably from non-contact sources. He sustained an abdominal abrasion and a splenic laceration from contact with the lap belt and transverse process fractures to L2 and L3 from contact with the shoulder belt (torso rotation). He sustained a left pubic symphysis fracture from left knee contact with the glove box door. He sustained a right femoral neck fracture from knee contact with the glove box door. He sustained fractures of the left distal tibia and fibula, a LisFranc foot fracture, a left cuboid fracture, a left calcaneous fracture, and a left 4th metatarsal fracture from contact with the toepan. The case occupants mass, the large amount of toe pan intrusion, and the high-energy impact were all thought to be contributing factors for the lower extremity injuries.
